265
00:12:17,476 --> 00:12:18,609
- Apologize.
- I'm sorry.

266
00:12:18,644 --> 00:12:20,011
- Mackenzie: <i>To Don.</i>
- I'm over it.

267
00:12:20,045 --> 00:12:21,212
Neal.

268
00:12:21,246 --> 00:12:23,347
There is an alternative
weekly in Spokane

269
00:12:23,381 --> 00:12:25,849
<i>called the "Pacific</i>
<i>Northwest Insider"</i>

270
00:12:25,884 --> 00:12:28,652
that published an article about
immigration a couple of weeks ago.

271
00:12:28,687 --> 00:12:31,222
The story featured a guy
named Hector Nunez

272
00:12:31,256 --> 00:12:33,257
who revealed that
when he was 16,

273
00:12:33,292 --> 00:12:35,426
his parents told him that
he was living here illegally.

274
00:12:35,460 --> 00:12:36,827
The paper used his real name?

275
00:12:36,862 --> 00:12:38,663
Yeah, and the state
of Washington rescinded

276
00:12:38,697 --> 00:12:40,831
his driver's license
after the piece came out.

277
00:12:40,866 --> 00:12:44,969
He needs his car to get to his
job with a small moving company

278
00:12:45,003 --> 00:12:47,104
and to take his kids
to school in the morning.

279
00:12:47,139 --> 00:12:48,906
I thought we could have him on.

280
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:50,607
I've got to budget 42 minutes.

281
00:12:50,675 --> 00:12:53,277
I've already spent 18
on Jan Brewer and La Raza.

282
00:12:53,311 --> 00:12:55,245
I thought we could put
a human face on immigration.

283
00:12:55,279 --> 00:12:57,381
How about putting a human face
on the guy whose job he took?

284
00:12:57,416 --> 00:12:58,917
Mackenzie:
<i>We don't have the time.</i>

285
00:12:58,951 --> 00:13:01,720
We've got 1070, BP,
and a Senate candidate

286
00:13:01,754 --> 00:13:03,489
who says poor people can pay
doctors with chickens.

287
00:13:03,523 --> 00:13:05,725
But even if we did have the time, it
would be emotionally manipulative.

288
00:13:05,759 --> 00:13:07,293
- How?
- We'd be putting him there

289
00:13:07,327 --> 00:13:08,794
so that we can feel
sorry for him.

290
00:13:08,829 --> 00:13:10,630
We should feel sorry for him.
He's getting screwed.

291
00:13:10,664 --> 00:13:12,399
You should feel sorry
for the guy whose job he took.

292
00:13:12,433 --> 00:13:13,967
I don't want to feel
sorry for anybody.

293
00:13:14,001 --> 00:13:17,403
I want the facts, and neither
of them can provide facts.

294
00:13:17,438 --> 00:13:19,239
- Somebody's gonna book this kid.
- Nobody's gonna book him.

295
00:13:19,273 --> 00:13:20,539
Nobody's gonna
have heard of him.

296
00:13:20,574 --> 00:13:22,174
It's an alternative
weekly in Spokane.

297
00:13:22,209 --> 00:13:25,845
And do you see "What's our
competition doing?" on the easel?

298
00:13:25,879 --> 00:13:27,881
- No, but I wish I did.
- Moving on.

299
00:13:30,985 --> 00:13:32,318
The Dow has ticked down
108 points

300
00:13:32,353 --> 00:13:34,454
on a surprisingly weak
durable-goods orders report

301
00:13:34,489 --> 00:13:36,556
from the Commerce Department
that has raised worries...

302
00:13:36,591 --> 00:13:39,626
Listen, I'm not gonna take it
from him in public or private.

303
00:13:39,660 --> 00:13:41,428
- I'm doing you guys a favor.
- I'm sorry.

304
00:13:41,462 --> 00:13:43,063
I understand.
And he knows that.

305
00:13:43,097 --> 00:13:44,865
You're cutting "PopWatch"
and "Today on YouTube"?

306
00:13:44,899 --> 00:13:46,900
I am. And I know
they're both yours, but--

307
00:13:46,968 --> 00:13:48,435
I don't care that they're mine.

308
00:13:48,469 --> 00:13:50,537
I care that they're the most
popular segments on the show.

309
00:13:50,571 --> 00:13:53,574
- Look at the minute to minutes.
- Feel free to use them when you and Elliot start at 10:00.

310
00:13:53,608 --> 00:13:55,608
Yeah, there's gonna be nobody left
at 10:00 if you lead off the night

311
00:13:55,643 --> 00:13:57,944
with the "Will McAvoy Makes You
Eat Your Vegetables Hour."

312
00:13:59,346 --> 00:14:02,815
- Hmm?
- Forget it.

313
00:14:04,985 --> 00:14:06,686
- Maggie.
- Yeah.

314
00:14:06,721 --> 00:14:08,722
Mac wants me to supervise your
preinterview with Brewer's office.

315
00:14:08,756 --> 00:14:11,191
- I was told.
- All right, you're gonna be talking to a spokesperson.

316
00:14:11,225 --> 00:14:14,828
- I'll call him now.
- I thought maybe we could do a practice run first.

317
00:14:14,863 --> 00:14:17,431
Okay, I'd like to say,
with all respect,

318
00:14:17,465 --> 00:14:19,600
that I don't feel I need
to be supervised.

319
00:14:19,634 --> 00:14:21,935
- Okay.
- You'll let me do it by myself?

320
00:14:21,969 --> 00:14:24,204
No, I just meant okay,
I heard you say that.

321
00:14:24,238 --> 00:14:26,373
I've been here a year.
You've been here three days.

322
00:14:26,407 --> 00:14:29,476
Mac's working with a group of relatively
inexperienced people she doesn't know.

323
00:14:29,510 --> 00:14:30,710
- I know that.
- All right.

324
00:14:30,745 --> 00:14:32,712
- So you'll let me do it myself?
- No.

325
00:14:32,747 --> 00:14:35,348
- Then I'm doing this under protest.
- I'm sorry?

326
00:14:35,382 --> 00:14:37,751
I'm just-- I'll be--
I'm doing this under protest.

327
00:14:37,785 --> 00:14:39,719
- What does that look like?
- It'll be the same.

328
00:14:39,754 --> 00:14:41,521
I'm just lodging
an official protest.

329
00:14:41,555 --> 00:14:43,623
- With who?
- My immediate superior, I guess.

330
00:14:43,657 --> 00:14:46,025
- That's me.
- Well, are you writing it down?

331
00:14:46,060 --> 00:14:48,194
No. Are you really
considering going to 10:00?

332
00:14:48,229 --> 00:14:50,931
- Don made some compelling arguments.
- Yeah? What were they?

333
00:14:50,965 --> 00:14:53,933
That growing something from scratch
is something I should experience.

334
00:14:53,968 --> 00:14:56,536
- ( laughs ) Okay.
- Whoa, whoa, wait.

335
00:14:56,570 --> 00:14:57,604
- What did that mean?
- Nothing.

336
00:14:57,638 --> 00:14:58,671
- Really?
- Yeah.

337
00:14:58,706 --> 00:15:00,774
I know exactly
what you're thinking.

338
00:15:00,808 --> 00:15:02,575
I can't say the same.

339
00:15:02,610 --> 00:15:04,444
- You don't think I'm making a relationship choice?
- No.

340
00:15:04,478 --> 00:15:06,112
That this is just
a temp gig for me

341
00:15:06,147 --> 00:15:09,349
until someone puts a ring
on it and I can have kids?

342
00:15:09,383 --> 00:15:11,318
I wasn't saying--
I didn't say any of that.

343
00:15:11,352 --> 00:15:14,220
You don't think that I don't have the
same commitment to news that you do?

344
00:15:14,255 --> 00:15:16,489
No.

345
00:15:16,524 --> 00:15:18,758
I'll be honest-- because of the
way I phrased those questions,

346
00:15:18,793 --> 00:15:20,927
I wasn't totally clear
on what your answers meant.

347
00:15:20,995 --> 00:15:23,829
I think that you have the same
commitment to the news that I do.

348
00:15:23,864 --> 00:15:25,664
I think kids are great.
I used to be one.

349
00:15:25,699 --> 00:15:27,467
And I can't remember
the third thing, but--

350
00:15:27,501 --> 00:15:29,068
- Ring, ring.
- Thank you.

351
00:15:29,103 --> 00:15:30,636
- Ring, ring.
- Hi, it's Glenn Fisher.

352
00:15:30,671 --> 00:15:32,171
- Glenn Fisher?
- Yes.

353
00:15:32,205 --> 00:15:33,806
- That's the spokesperson I'm talking to?
- Yes.

354
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:35,074
I thought it was John Markell.

355
00:15:35,108 --> 00:15:36,775
Fisher's a press agent
who's doing the preinterview.

356
00:15:36,810 --> 00:15:38,878
Okay.

357
00:15:38,912 --> 00:15:41,446
First, you go into iNews
and you look over the questions

358
00:15:41,481 --> 00:15:43,181
the segment producer
put in the rundown.

359
00:15:43,216 --> 00:15:46,385
Identify yourself and your news
agency, summarize the segment--

360
00:15:46,419 --> 00:15:47,953
the length,
whether it's live or not,

361
00:15:47,987 --> 00:15:50,089
and who we're having on
from the other side.

362
00:15:50,123 --> 00:15:53,091
I'm sorry, but don't I first open
my eyes and notice it's a new day?

363
00:15:53,126 --> 00:15:54,559
- What are we talking about here?
- I've done this before.

364
00:15:54,594 --> 00:15:57,128
- Okay.
- What is this magic box in front of me?

365
00:15:57,163 --> 00:15:58,730
Have I done something to you?

366
00:15:58,764 --> 00:16:00,531
I swear I was just thinking
the exact same thing.

367
00:16:00,566 --> 00:16:02,367
I have no idea why
I'm being mean to you.

368
00:16:02,401 --> 00:16:03,835
Now that you know that,
do you think you'll stop?

369
00:16:03,869 --> 00:16:05,470
That's the thing--
it doesn't feel like it.

370
00:16:05,504 --> 00:16:06,771
I'm just being honest.

371
00:16:06,805 --> 00:16:08,639
I can't ask for more than that,
except rational thought.

372
00:16:08,674 --> 00:16:10,241
- What was that?
- Nothing.

373
00:16:10,275 --> 00:16:11,876
- Ring, ring.
- Hi, it's Glenn Fisher.

374
00:16:11,910 --> 00:16:13,777
Glenn, this is Margaret Jordan.

375
00:16:13,812 --> 00:16:16,580
I'm an associate producer at "News
Night" and I'm doing the preinterview

376
00:16:16,614 --> 00:16:18,248
for the governor's
appearance this evening.

377
00:16:18,283 --> 00:16:21,552
I know Will's gonna
wanna ask why mean people

378
00:16:21,586 --> 00:16:23,620
tend to pour into your state
like it's a bathtub drain.

379
00:16:23,654 --> 00:16:25,255
Will's not gonna
wanna ask that.

380
00:16:25,289 --> 00:16:27,924
I think they're building the fence
on the wrong side of the state.

381
00:16:27,959 --> 00:16:30,193
Margaret, here in Arizona,
the government can barely pay

382
00:16:30,228 --> 00:16:32,029
for the needs of native-born
poor as it is--

383
00:16:32,063 --> 00:16:33,663
welfare, education,
Social Security--

384
00:16:33,698 --> 00:16:35,232
especially when
so many households here

385
00:16:35,266 --> 00:16:37,301
are one or two paychecks away
from the poverty line.

386
00:16:37,335 --> 00:16:38,769
You're scapegoating
these people.

387
00:16:38,804 --> 00:16:41,606
Stop. I just said
illegals cost money.

388
00:16:41,640 --> 00:16:45,042
- Ask the follow-up.
- Okay.

389
00:16:45,077 --> 00:16:47,445
Ask it.

390
00:16:47,479 --> 00:16:50,081
My follow-up,
Mr. Fisher, is this--

391
00:16:50,115 --> 00:16:53,784
I understand that having undocumented
workers living in the US costs money

392
00:16:53,819 --> 00:16:56,186
and it's a problem we have
to do something about,

393
00:16:56,221 --> 00:16:58,388
but shouldn't it be a point
of pride for Americans

394
00:16:58,422 --> 00:17:01,057
that others are willing to uproot
their families just to come here?

395
00:17:01,091 --> 00:17:03,559
The follow-up was
"How much do they cost?"

396
00:17:03,593 --> 00:17:06,429
But, yes, it is a point of pride
that people wanna come to America

397
00:17:06,496 --> 00:17:08,531
and we value our diverse
population in Arizona,

398
00:17:08,565 --> 00:17:10,833
but we just want people to immigrate
legally and become citizens.

399
00:17:10,867 --> 00:17:13,669
And I'm sure that's what's behind
the emotion and the vitriol--

400
00:17:13,704 --> 00:17:15,972
Americans hate it when people don't
fill out the proper paperwork.

401
00:17:16,006 --> 00:17:20,009
- You can't antagonize the--
- <i>I'm gonna ask the right questions, you dweeb!</i>

402
00:17:20,044 --> 00:17:21,911
- And you'll follow up?
- I'll follow up.

403
00:17:21,946 --> 00:17:25,816
My point is that whatever side
of this you're on,

404
00:17:25,850 --> 00:17:29,686
the rhetoric we use to talk about
these people who risk their lives

405
00:17:29,721 --> 00:17:31,054
to have a shot
at picking oranges

406
00:17:31,089 --> 00:17:33,256
so their kids have a shot
at not being dead

407
00:17:33,291 --> 00:17:35,358
makes it sound like
we're talking about

408
00:17:35,393 --> 00:17:38,095
scraping gum off our shoes.

409
00:17:38,129 --> 00:17:42,065
These people chose to take a
huge risk to become Americans

410
00:17:42,099 --> 00:17:44,902
and they deserve a better
descriptor than "illegals."

411
00:17:52,077 --> 00:17:53,911
You don't need me.
You got this one.

412
00:17:53,945 --> 00:17:55,779
Thank you.

413
00:17:55,814 --> 00:17:58,449
Sloan: <i>Another story making headlines
this morning is, of course, Greece,</i>

414
00:17:58,484 --> 00:18:01,019
whose prime minister officially
requested activation

415
00:18:01,053 --> 00:18:02,887
of the EU/IMF bailout package,

416
00:18:02,922 --> 00:18:04,922
lifting the euro from
its lowest level of the year

417
00:18:04,957 --> 00:18:06,557
and sending
commodity prices soaring.

418
00:18:06,592 --> 00:18:08,793
We'll have that and the rest
of the day's financial news

419
00:18:08,828 --> 00:18:10,428
on "Market Wrap-Up"
at 4:00.

420
00:18:10,462 --> 00:18:11,796
I'm Sloan Sabbith.

421
00:18:11,830 --> 00:18:14,265
Let's go out to Diane
and Billy on the West Coast

422
00:18:14,300 --> 00:18:15,834
for Atlantis Hollywood.

423
00:18:15,868 --> 00:18:17,936
Man:
<i>And we're clear.</i>

424
00:18:20,072 --> 00:18:22,575
- Hello.
- Sloan, I'm Mackenzie McHale.

425
00:18:22,609 --> 00:18:24,910
- I know. It's good to meet you.
- It's nice to meet you.

426
00:18:24,945 --> 00:18:27,546
- Do you have a minute?
- Sure. Thanks.

427
00:18:29,483 --> 00:18:32,051
Mackenzie: <i>You know, I was watching you
earlier when you were talking about</i>

428
00:18:32,086 --> 00:18:34,487
<i>two companies--</i>
<i>Capital One and, um--</i>

429
00:18:34,522 --> 00:18:36,122
- Baxter.
- Baxter.

430
00:18:36,156 --> 00:18:38,524
And the prompter said, "Both of
whom are hinting at good numbers,"

431
00:18:38,559 --> 00:18:41,193
and you said, "Both of <i>which</i>
are hinting at good numbers."

432
00:18:41,228 --> 00:18:43,929
- Was that an accident?
- No. I didn't write that copy.

433
00:18:43,997 --> 00:18:46,332
I changed it to "which"
because "whom" is for people.

434
00:18:46,366 --> 00:18:48,234
- Is someone in trouble?
- No.

435
00:18:48,268 --> 00:18:51,337
- Do you mind coming into my office for a second?
- Sure.

436
00:18:51,371 --> 00:18:54,207
What's the difference between
a corporation and a person?

437
00:18:54,241 --> 00:18:56,409
- Have you ever held a door open for someone?
- Yes.

438
00:18:56,443 --> 00:18:58,311
- Did you ask them for money first?
- No.

439
00:18:58,345 --> 00:19:00,246
- That's the difference.
- That's the right answer.

440
00:19:00,281 --> 00:19:02,916
- Am I taking a test?
- I've asked around and people say

441
00:19:02,950 --> 00:19:04,651
you don't belong here,
that you could be making

442
00:19:04,685 --> 00:19:06,686
a lot more money
as an analyst at Goldman.

443
00:19:06,720 --> 00:19:09,088
Couldn't you be making a lot more
money producing reality television?

444
00:19:09,123 --> 00:19:12,426
I do produce
reality television.

445
00:19:12,460 --> 00:19:14,061
I don't know what to tell you.

446
00:19:14,095 --> 00:19:15,129
I like my job.

447
00:19:15,163 --> 00:19:17,364
Do you feel like
working longer hours?

448
00:19:17,399 --> 00:19:19,433
They talked to me about
doing a morning show

449
00:19:19,467 --> 00:19:21,001
a couple of times,
but I can't do that.

450
00:19:21,036 --> 00:19:23,337
I'm not interested in cooking.
I make sandwiches.

451
00:19:23,372 --> 00:19:26,440
I get that I don't necessarily look
like it, but I'm an economist.

452
00:19:26,475 --> 00:19:29,010
- Thanks, though.
- Yeah, I meant in prime time.

453
00:19:29,044 --> 00:19:32,080
I want to give you
five minutes every night

454
00:19:32,114 --> 00:19:34,616
to talk about where we are
and how we got here.

455
00:19:34,650 --> 00:19:36,485
Are you serious?

456
00:19:37,787 --> 00:19:39,254
There are people
more qualified than I am.

457
00:19:39,289 --> 00:19:41,657
I can put you in touch with some of
the professors that I studied under--

458
00:19:41,691 --> 00:19:45,861
Yeah, the thing is they're
not going to have your legs.

459
00:19:45,895 --> 00:19:49,598
I'm sorry, but if I'm going to get
people to listen to an economics lesson,

460
00:19:49,633 --> 00:19:52,568
I've got to find someone who doesn't
